  "prompt": "How cold can the Gobi Desert get, and how do its average temperatures compare to the ones in the Great Basin Desert?",
  "response": "The Gobi Desert, located in northern China and southern Mongolia, experiences extreme temperature fluctuations due to its continental climate. In winter, temperatures can plummet to as low as **-40\u00b0C (-40\u00b0F)** or even lower in some parts, making it one of the coldest deserts in the world. Summers, on the other hand, can be quite hot, with temperatures reaching up to **45\u00b0C (113\u00b0F)**.\n\nThe Great Basin Desert, located in the western United States, also has a continental climate but generally experiences less extreme cold compared to the Gobi. Winter temperatures in the Great Basin typically range from **-10\u00b0C (14\u00b0F)** to **10\u00b0C (50\u00b0F)**, depending on elevation and specific location. Summers are warm, with average highs around **30\u00b0C (86\u00b0F)**, though some areas can exceed **38\u00b0C (100\u00b0F)**.\n\n### Comparison:\n1. **Winter Cold**:\n   - The Gobi Desert is significantly colder in winter, often reaching **-40\u00b0C (-40\u00b0F)** or lower.\n   - The Great Basin Desert is milder, with winter lows usually staying above **-10\u00b0C (14\u00b0F)**.\n\n2. **Summer Heat**:\n   - Both deserts can experience hot summers, but the Gobi tends to be slightly hotter, with temperatures exceeding **45\u00b0C (113\u00b0F)**.\n   - The Great Basin\u2019s summer highs are generally in the **30\u00b0C to 38\u00b0C (86\u00b0F to 100\u00b0F)** range.\n\n3. **Annual Temperature Range**:\n   - The Gobi has a more extreme annual temperature range due to its harsher winters and hotter summers.\n   - The Great Basin has a narrower range, with more moderate seasonal variations.\n\nIn summary, the Gobi Desert is much colder in winter and slightly hotter in summer compared to the Great Basin Desert, reflecting its more extreme continental climate.",
